78369 - Khizriel Following battle-tested Angel Cartel doctrines, the Khizriel-class battlecruiser makes a virtue out of speed of striking and the ability to rain destruction on its targets from just out of reach of any counterfire. Engineers of the Cartel's Salvation Angels group have labored on this design's warp drive to eke out every last bit of acceleration and warp speed possible for such a large ship. While this gunboat lacks the flexibility of missile options, it is able to deploy a covering flight of drones should it need to distract and disrupt any enemies.

The speed and formidable firepower of the Khizriel is enhanced by top-of-the-line shield and armor systems protecting an unusually agile battlecruiser. The Khizriel's ability to strike from surprise, destroy its targets, and rapidly evade reprisals may be unmatched among pirate vessels, and is clearly intended to be a serious thorn in the side of empire border patrols and CONCORD security forces. 78622 - Gravid Vorton Tuning System Mutaplasmid This bioadaptive mutaplasmid tool is the product of an extensive research program by Upwell Consortium nanoengineers working with a variety of recovered Triglavian mutaplasmid strains. The resultant mutaplasmid tool is designed to interface with and alter devices which provide stable fire control for vorton projectors. As such this mutaplasmid could be used to mutate the performance characteristics of vorton tuning system modules and has been made available to all participating member states of EDENCOM.

Triglavian bioadaptive technology makes extensive use of engineered colonies of extremophilic bacteria, that are used to grow, harvest and adapt various resources found in Abyssal Deadspace. Artificial colonizing plasmids integrated into specialist tools used for direct adaptation of technology can be found in Triglavian caches in various stages of development. These mutaplasmids can be used to alter the characteristics of a wide variety of equipment types, depending on the strain and the bioadaptive tool with which they are integrated.

The mutaplasmid colony integrated into this bioadaptive tool appears to be mature and reproducing at a healthy rate. The mutational benefits and risks of using this mutaplasmid are within relatively balanced bounds.		 Mutaplasmids

79508 - Upwell Fortification Variant 'Kingbird' Working through its member corporations within each of the "Big 4" empires, the Upwell Consortium has secured contracts to enhance counter-insurgency efforts against marauding pirate gangs and their capsuleer supporters. Analyzing the problem of responding to pirate insurgencies, taking into account lessons learned by fortification efforts during the Triglavian Invasions, the Upwell Consortium chose to source a large quantity of Bustard-class hulls from the Lai Dai corporation.

As a highly-protected but less massive hulls than the large Orca-class, the ship provided a sound basis for a variant class of fortification constructor aimed at enhancing the ability of empires to assert their sovereignty against pirate insurgents: the "Kingbird". The ship was then specially adapted to be able to deploy and service the counter-insurgency weapons platforms that are placed at strategic locations within systems where anti-pirate operations have elevated the system suppression to high levels. 134268 You can make multiple consecutive jumps through stargates much more quickly manually than you can relying on Autopilot (because the Autopilot brings your ship out of warp 15 km from the stargate each time you warp, forcing you to then fly at sub-warp speed to within 2,500 m of the gate before jumping).


First, set your destination by right-clicking on the location in the journal entry or in your bookmarks. The correct stargate icon will now be highlighted in yellow, both in your overview and in space.


Now, right-click on the stargate (either in space or in the overview) and use the "Warp to within 0 km" option… and then turn on Autopilot; you will drop out of warp directly beside the stargate and, because Autopilot is on, jump immediately. As soon as you begin to jump, turn your Autopilot back off; once you've jumped, simply repeat the whole "Warp to 0 km" process with each stargate along the route until you arrive at your destination system. 134493 The easiest way to travel to a destination system quickly is to use the Overview. Stargates are marked in the Overview settings panel under the "Celestial" group; once you have selected "Stargate" there, right-click on the hyperlinked destination system in your mission journal and choose "Set destination." You will notice that the next stargate along your route, both in space and in your Overview, is now yellow.


Next, right-click on the yellow stargate (in space or in the Overview) and select "Warp to within 0m"; turn on your Autopilot, then sit back and relax until you are in the destination system.


After you have completed the mission, if you have problems finding your way back to the agent, simply open the "People and Places" window from your NeoCom and check the Agents tab; the agent you are working for should be displayed there. 134915 The easiest way to travel to a destination station quickly is to use the Overview. Stargates are marked in the Overview settings panel under the "Celestial" group. Once you have selected "stargate" in the Overview settings, right-click on the hyperlinked destination system in your mission journal and choose "set destination." You will notice that the applicable stargate in your Overview is now yellow, as well as the one in space that leads to the next system along your route.


Next, simply right-click on the yellow stargate in the Overview (or in space) and hit "warp to within 0m"; turn on your Autopilot and simply sit back and relax until you are in the destination system.


Once you have arrived in the correct star system, simply right-click anywhere in space. In the drop-down window that appears, your current mission information appears at the bottom. From there, select the "dock" option and your Autopilot will bring you into the station momentarily.

530039 Representing an escalation in Blood Raider Covenant activity across the core territories of the Amarr Empire, and neighboring regions of high-security space, the establishment of Blood Raider Forward Operating Bases poses a severe threat to core empire interests.

In particular, Blood Raider mining operations and patrol fleets are able to range out from such FOBs in ever greater numbers, striking in asteroid belts and against vulnerable infrastructure.

CONCORD has assessed the threat of pirate FOBs as extremely serious and will reward capsuleer groups that take the lead in degrading and destroying outlaw structures of this kind.

The capsuleer fleet that inflicts the most damage on a pirate FOB will receive up to <color=yellow>800,000,000 ISK</color>, with individual pilots potentially receiving up to <color=yellow>30,000,000 ISK</color> each. A novel and powerful addition to the range of neural boosters available to capsuleers, the Agency's ‘Pyrolancea’ compounds introduce a temporary but highly adaptive neural lace into the user’s synaptic structures. This 'Pyrolancea' lace enhances neural centers involved in calibration of munitions payloads and weapons energy profiles on the fly during high-intensity combat. The increase in the processing available to the capsuleer means that payload calibration solutions can be tailored more finely and results in improved damage yields against any given target.

Compounds with the Agency identifier are being seeded into target locations identified by the mysterious network ahead of sponsored operations. Entities occupying the target sites often collect the Agency's support drops themselves even if they realize what they must portend. 569365 This Abyssal Filament will pull a Tech I or Tech II Cruiser into a pocket of Abyssal Deadspace experiencing cataclysmic local environmental destabilizationand clouded by a field of dark matter that will reduce weapon ranges but enhance ship velocity.

<color=yellow>Warning:</color> Abyssal Deadspace is a particularly harsh and unforgiving environment. Entanglement of the warp core with a space-time filament introduces severe deformations of the ship's warp field that cumulatively increase over time. After <color=yellow>20 minutes</color> catastrophic collapse of the warp field is predicted, with <color=yellow>destruction of the ship and capsule</color> certain.

A device of Triglavian design that functions as one end of an energetically inert filament of space-time connected to a specific pocket of Abyssal Deadspace. When activated by a ship equipped with a warp core that has the correct mass-energy parameters, the filament becomes a conduit that will draw the activating vessel along it and into the connected deadspace pocket.

The mass-energy exchange involved leaves a highly energetic trace at the ship's origin point and the space-time filament remains entangled with the warp core of the ship that uses it. Triglavian Transfer Conduits will permit such a ship to progress through the deadspace pocket but an Origin Conduit will return the ship to its starting location in normal space. 664933 Following battle-tested Angel Cartel doctrines, the Khizriel-class battlecruiser makes a virtue out of speed of striking and the ability to rain destruction on its targets from just out of reach of any counterfire. 666371 Gravid Vorton Tuning System Mutaplasmid Gravid Vorton Tuning System Mutaplasmid Name of item 78622 (Mutaplasmids)
666372 This bioadaptive mutaplasmid tool is the product of an extensive research program by Upwell Consortium nanoengineers working with a variety of recovered Triglavian mutaplasmid strains. The resultant mutaplasmid tool is designed to interface with and alter devices which provide stable fire control for vorton projectors. As such this mutaplasmid could be used to mutate the performance characteristics of vorton tuning system modules and has been made available to all participating member states of EDENCOM.

Triglavian bioadaptive technology makes extensive use of engineered colonies of extremophilic bacteria, that are used to grow, harvest and adapt various resources found in Abyssal Deadspace. Artificial colonizing plasmids integrated into specialist tools used for direct adaptation of technology can be found in Triglavian caches in various stages of development. These mutaplasmids can be used to alter the characteristics of a wide variety of equipment types, depending on the strain and the bioadaptive tool with which they are integrated.

The mutaplasmid colony integrated into this bioadaptive tool appears to be mature and reproducing at a healthy rate. The mutational benefits and risks of using this mutaplasmid are within relatively balanced bounds. 666855 Pirate insurgencies begin in the warzones where continuous war has destabilized the region – making systems in those regions attractive targets for pirate attacks. At the start of an insurgency, the pirate faction places an FOB in orbit around a temperate planet in the warzone and selects several systems nearby as their initial targets.

As pirate-aligned players raid these systems, they will increase the Corruption of the system. Similarly, as militia players push back against the pirate insurgents, they will increase the Suppression value of the system. As corruption is increased, the systems targeted by the pirate faction will expand to include new systems, these new systems may even include systems beyond the warzone or in high security space!

When Corruption reaches its maximum value, the system is deemed fully pillaged and the pirates score a point of progress towards their final goal. When Suppression reaches its maximum value, the system is deemed ‘secured’ and the anti-pirate militia factions score a point of progress towards making the pirate Forward Operating Base (FOB) vulnerable.

If the pirates are able to fully corrupt their target number of systems before the insurgency ends then they will be victorious – rewarding all contributing pirate players with a share of their spoils. This failure also weakens the FOB system, allowing the pirates to temporarily seize full control of the system – removing it from Faction Warfare while their hoard is returned to their base of operations in Zarzakh. If however the FOB is destroyed before they reach their goals, the insurgency will end and the empires will reward participating militia players for their aid. 669869 OVERVIEW OVERVIEW UI/Agency/PirateIncursions/Guides/Overview/OverviewSectionTitle
669870 During Pirate Insurgencies, pirate factions face off against the empires, each side attempting to 'score' systems by increasing the system's Corruption (pirates) or Suppression (militias) stages through the completion of various activities and objectives. As Corruption and Suppression increase in a system, they will have various effects on that system, for more details on these effects see the Corruption and Suppression section of this guide.

Insurgencies are struggles between pirates and militias with winning and losing sides. If the militias destroy the FOB before the pirates reach their goal, the empires are victorious. The FOB only becomes vulnerable once the militias have reached their goal. If the militias fail to destroy the FOB before the pirates succeed, the pirates are declared victorious. Once a victor has been declared, the insurgency will come to an end before a new insurgency begins after some time, in a new starting location.

There are two separate warzones where insurgencies may begin, one in the Caldari-Gallente warzone, where the Guristas Pirates are operating, and the other in the Amarr-Minmatar warzone, where the Angel Cartel is active. Each faction active in a warzone is at war with the other two. Guristas, Caldari and Gallente are all at war with one another, as are the Angels, Minmatar and Amarr. Pilots enlisted with any of these factions will be able to freely engage pilots aligned with those they are at war with, and will earn LP with their faction for completing insurgency activities. 669871 ANGEL CARTEL AND GURISTAS PIRATES ANGEL CARTEL AND GURISTAS PIRATES UI/Agency/PirateIncursions/Guides/Factions/PiratesSectionTitle
669872 The Angel Cartel and Guristas Pirates have begun recruiting ‘eggers’ (capsuleers) to participate in their insurgency campaigns against the empires. Pilots can enlist with one of these pirate factions to participate in insurgencies while earning valuable LP with their chosen faction.

Each pirate faction is at war with two empire factions. The Guristas are at war with the Caldari and Gallente; the Angel Cartel is at war with the Minmatar and Amarr. Joining a pirate faction will give you the freedom to shoot (and be shot by) members of the enemy empires without CONCORD interference. In addition, be aware that empire military police will attack in an enemy empire hisec system unless the insurgency has spread into it.

Both the Angels and Guristas have a minimum faction standings requirement of -2.0 for enlistment. If your standings are too low, you will be unable to enlist. As an insurgent, your enlistment may be revoked if your standings fall. Standings can be gained with these factions by completing their Epic Arc missions, allowing you a chance to repair your standings and re-enlist with the faction. 669873 ZARZAKH ZARZAKH UI/Agency/PirateIncursions/Guides/Factions/ZarzakhSectionTitle
669874 Thanks to their alliance with the Deathless Circle, the Angel Cartel and Guristas have privileged access to Zarzakh. The system is serving as the base of operations for both factions' insurgency initiatives, as the pirates use its Jovian stargates to quickly spread chaos and corruption throughout New Eden.

Pilots enlisted with a pirate faction are exempted from the toll which is normally required to access the system and have special privileges in the Fulcrum, the Jovian station now controlled by the Deathless. This special access includes clone bay and LP store access for their factions, as well as manufacturing cost discounts when building pirate faction ships in the station.

Pirate-aligned pilots also have access to the Deathless Shipcaster in Zarzakh, which will quickly take them from their faction's base in Zarzakh directly out to their faction’s Forward Operating Base (FOB), allowing rapid access to Insurgency activities. 669921 ZARZAKH OVERVIEW ZARZAKH OVERVIEW UI/Agency/Zarzakh/Guides/Overview/OverviewSectionTitle
669922 Zarzakh is a system cloaked in the dust, gas and assorted other bits of matter that are being drawn towards the black hole known as "Point of No Return" to most of New Eden, and "Duzna Kah" to the Amarr. The location of Zarzakh places it deep in the void of Divinity's Edge, or "Yasna Zakh", and somewhat notably, essentially at the center of the New Eden cluster by virtue of the astronomical co-ordinate system used by CONCORD. Given this system was proposed by the Jove in the early days of CONCORD, it is suggestive that the dominating features of Zarzakh are the ancient Jovian gates and the ancient Jovian outpost known as "The Fulcrum".

The Zarzakh star system is wracked by severe gravitational effects rendering most locations unsafe for any ship to stop at. Safe locations are to be found at the ancient Jovian stargates, station, and shipcaster site. With these safe zones under the control of the Deathless Circle, Zarzakh is a formidable pirate haven. 669925 Zarzakh's star has been gravitationally captured by a black hole and is slowly orbiting closer and closer to its eventual merger with the mass singularity. This event will take place many years in the future but the effects of orbiting in the relatively near vicinity of a black hole are already being felt in the form of intense and volatile gravitational tidal forces exerted by the singularity. As the star is within the outer edges of the matter accretion disc of the black hole, the instability is further contributed to by the fluctuations in mass density within the cloud. The local system environment here is harsh and unforgiving to say the least.

669962 GRAVITY HAZARD & SAFE ZONES GRAVITY HAZARD & SAFE ZONES UI/Agency/Zarzakh/Guides/Zones/ZonesSectionTitle
669963 Gravity Hazard
As a whole, the Zarzakh system is subject to an intense gravity hazard that will rapidly tear apart the hull of any spaceship experiencing the local volatile tidal forces and spacetime distortions. These damaging forces can be briefly mitigated by structural integrity systems before rapidly escalating to inevitable destruction of the vessel.

Safe Zones
Despite the forbidding dangers of the gravity hazard, a number of safe zones can be found in Zarzakh. Each of these zones is centered on ancient Jovian infrastructure that generate local protection fields around them. Safe zones are located at each of the four Jovian stargates, the Fulcrum station, and around a Jovian Observatory orbiting the star. The Deathless Shipcaster is located in the safe zone at the star.		 <b>Gravity Hazard</b>

669966 TOLLS & RESTRICTIONS TOLLS & RESTRICTIONS UI/Agency/Zarzakh/Guides/Jovian/TollsSectionTitle
669967 Under the control of the Deathless Circle, the incoming stargates located in <url=showinfo:5//30003841>Alsavoinon</url>, <url=showinfo:5//30001041>G-0Q86</url>, <url=showinfo:5//30001269>H-PA29</url>, and <url=showinfo:5//30002086>Turnur</url> charge a toll in ISK based on the mass of the incoming spaceship. Outgoing stargates do not charge this toll. Pirate-aligned pilots are exempt from paying this toll.

674135 Insurgencies are dynamically generated combat zones where pilots who are aligned with a pirate faction raid systems owned by the empires. These conflicts start in low security warzone systems, but may spread to other areas of space.

679540 Insurgencies Insurgencies UI/Agency/PirateIncursions/Guides/Insurgencies/InsurgenciesSectionTitle
679541 During Pirate Insurgencies, pirate factions face off against the empires, each side attempting to 'score' systems by increasing the system's Corruption (pirates) or Suppression (militias) value through the completion of various activities and objectives. Each faction has an independent target score they are looking to reach to allow them to win the insurgency, with the minimum score required to win increasing for a faction as they win multiple events.

An insurgency starts with the placement of a pirate Forward Operating Base (FOB) in the warzone. Several systems are then selected adjacent to the FOB system as initial insurgency targets. This begins the ‘Forecasting Period'. The insurgency does not become immediately active, giving both pirate and militia capsuleers time to move ships into position and otherwise prepare themselves for the event.

Once the forecasting period ends, the main phase of the Insurgency begins. Insurgency activities begin spawning and both pirate and militia players are able to contest them. Each Insurgency activity is worth a number off Corruption or Suppression points. As pirates complete objectives they will increase the Corruption value of the system; as militia players complete insurgency activities they will increase the Suppression value of the system. A system reaching maximum Corruption scores a point for the pirates while a system reaching maximum Suppression scores a point for the empires.

When the Corruption value of a system hits stage 3 during an Insurgency event, the insurgency will spread - adding a new system to the growing insurgency zone - a new target for the pirates. Activities will begin spawning in this system immediately. This dynamic spread will prefer systems adjacent to the system which triggered the spread if possible and will not spread to systems with a security status of 0.8 and higher or 0.0 and lower.

When the pirates reach their target score they are deemed the winners of the insurgency. All systems with active insurgency will see their Corruption value increased to the next stage and the pirates will seize the FOB system as their own - removing it from the FW warzone and causing neighboring systems to become frontlines (see Factional Warfare guide for further information on frontline status). After some time, the pirates will then abandon this system, tenuously returning it to the previous owner with control at minimum and the infrastructure hub vulnerable.

If the empires reach their target score however, then the pirate FOB becomes vulnerable. The FOB has a single armor reinforcement timer and, when destroyed, will result in defeat for the pirates and victory for the empires. Following a victory by the empires, all systems in the insurgency will see their Suppression value raise by one level for some time before the event comes to a close.

There are additional rewards for players on both sides who participate in an insurgency. Participation rewards can be tracked from the insurgency window, with larger rewards paying out to players who participated on the winning faction.		 During Pirate Insurgencies, pirate factions face off against the empires, each side attempting to 'score' systems by increasing the system's Corruption (pirates) or Suppression (militias) value through the completion of various activities and objectives. Each faction has an independent target score they are looking to reach to allow them to win the insurgency, with the minimum score required to win increasing for a faction as they win multiple events.

696805 Upwell Fortification Variant 'Kingbird' Upwell Fortification Variant 'Kingbird' Name of item 79508 (Insurgency Roaming Enforcers)
696806 Working through its member corporations within each of the "Big 4" empires, the Upwell Consortium has secured contracts to enhance counter-insurgency efforts against marauding pirate gangs and their capsuleer supporters. Analyzing the problem of responding to pirate insurgencies, taking into account lessons learned by fortification efforts during the Triglavian Invasions, the Upwell Consortium chose to source a large quantity of Bustard-class hulls from the Lai Dai corporation.

As a highly-protected but less massive hulls than the large Orca-class, the ship provided a sound basis for a variant class of fortification constructor aimed at enhancing the ability of empires to assert their sovereignty against pirate insurgents: the "Kingbird". The ship was then specially adapted to be able to deploy and service the counter-insurgency weapons platforms that are placed at strategic locations within systems where anti-pirate operations have elevated the system suppression to high levels. 697074 In a corporate outpost raid activity, pirates NPCs are attacking corporate structures which are defended by Mordus Legion security forces. Players can destroy the NPCs of the opposing faction to spin down the timer in their favor - seizing control of the outpost. For pirate aligned players, no progress can be made while Mordus NPCs or empire militia pilots are guarding the facility.

Likewise, for empire-aligned militia players, no progress can be made to secure the site while pirate NPCs or pirate aligned players are within range. The timer for this site is a direct tug-of-war contest, as one side needs to wind back the progress the other has made before being able to win. Players must remain within the capture radius to make progress.
